description.text:
I have heard many complaints about how the Z axis of the Prusa I2 and others, hangs from the motor shaft coupler and can often slip due to all that weight pulling it down. At least one person has had their X axis fall off completely.  
This shaft coupler is a modified version of one presented by nophead with the difference being that it has two high strength neodymium magnets locked inside of it.  
To use it simply allow the motor shaft to come into contact with one side of the magnets, and the lead screw to come into contact with the other side of the magnets.  The magnets alone should be able to support the weight of the Z-axis and print heads even before you tighten the screws to lock the shafts to the coupler.  
The ends of the metal shafts should be as flat and perpendicular as possible to ensure that they make strong contact with the magnets.  
***** Important up date - apparently not all stepper motors have a ferrous metal shaft. I have one that must be stainless steel, and thus will not benefit from this design.

description.text: I just designed this part that climbs up the printer at the end of the print job, as an experiment to design and develop more dynamic prints. Have any printer climber ideas? See what you can do with this idea! More detailed instructions and explanations here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_NhnYf9Viiw&feature=youtu.be or here: https://printeraction.wordpress.com/2015/03/04/printerference/

NOTE: Orient the part as shown in the MakerBot Desktop image, print horizontally. First place this spring: http://www.mcmaster.com/#9654k127/=w5xkt0
or something similar to it into the print as it is printing the spring pillars. Once the main segment of the print is done, remove the front hook piece and back latch piece from the plate, and slide the latch into the groove on the bottom of the hook piece. Let the rest pan out and watch your print pull itself off the plate! More detailed instructions in the video or here: https://printeraction.wordpress.com/2015/03/04/printerference/

description.text: This is a multicolor remix of Byctrldesign's design (found here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:525066). I printed it using ReplicatorG and a Flashforge Creator Pro. It's in red and black ABS. 5% infill.Both colors extruded at 235°C with the heated bed at 80°C.

In ReplicatorG, Select Gcode from the menu, then Select Merge .stl for DualExtrusion. Browse to the stls for the left and right extruder. I used the left extruder as the outer color and the right extruder as the inner color. Select a path for the gcode and click Merge. You'll get two slicing options boxes, configure them as you normally would. I used 5% infill and 235°C extrude temps. (Use whatever extruder temp works best for your printer and color) Once it's done, I manually edit the gcode to drop the headed bed temp. (If I run it at the default 110C, my prints curl up)
Change the S110 to S80 (or whatever works best for your printer) M109 S80 T0 (set HBP temperature) Print it and enjoy a multicolored phone holder.

description.text: A remix of http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:231725 to work with a Kossel 2020 delta printer. Holder has a quick removal connection and contains 2 12x28x8mm bearings that you can get on ebay or Amazon for a couple bucks each, for super smooth low-friction movement. I got 2 bearings delivered for $3.30 here: http://www.ebay.com/itm/231075663249 I remade the attachment for fit my Kossel delta printer with 2020 extrusions. The spool holder does not extend straight out from the tower, but is offset to alow the filament to feed off the spool more inline with the extruder motor. It has worked flawlessly since I installed it. The only tip I can give is this: the weight of the spool tends to cause the holder to flex a bit at the attachment. Installing a tiny washer or 2 bewteen the bottom of the mounting bracket and the tower to push out the bracket and thus angling the bracket up a couple degrees will result in a perfectly level holder once the spool is placed on it. This prevents the spool from walking to the outside of the holder.

description.text:
In a busy household with crazy schedules, sometimes it is difficult to know whether the dishwasher is clean or dirty. Unfortunately, the typical solution of using a magnet on the front that indicates clean/dirty does not work because a magnet does not stick to stainless steel.   
I was trying to think of an idea that would clip to the dishwasher and stumbled upon TechShopJim's design to use a clip on the dishwasher door.   
I love the design and decided to create something similar that would fit my Kenmore Elite dishwasher door thickness of 54mm. I printed this using ABS on my Printrbot Metal Plus with support enabled without any issues. The support broke away easily.

My dishwasher's door is approximately 54mm thick and the model is about 20mm wide. I found this slips easily on to my dishwasher and stays in place.   
Before I print a large model that takes 30+ minutes, I always model a small prototype that verifies any dimensions so I can quickly iterate and get the model just right. I've also included the test clip so you can test for a fit on your dishwasher before printing full model.

title: Davinci Da Vinci 1.0 E3D Carriage and Extruder drop in replacement

description.text:
Update August 14th, added the LM8UU version, although I have NOT TESTED it. Also I included a picture showing how the level arm is NOT solid, rather is has a shell of support material that breaks away really easily. Update, March 10th, 2015: updated minor parts of the assembly and added some final parts (z adapter for the optical switch, pin for the extruder lever arm). Added pictures of it in action. One of the best I think I've ever made. Eveything worked on the first try. Switching from a 40x40mm fan to 30x30mm made it fit much better and interfere less with the frame. Make sure to use a small screw with the z optical switch adapter (or use the minimalist one that just pushes on). I'd love to hear input! Mines working great. I've printed Taulman Tritan and PCTPE, gold and silver PLA, Polycarbonate (still trying to get better adhesion - best I've gotten is with kapton with abs-juice at 110/280/45 bed/hotend/chamber) Intro:
I wanted to print PLA (and nylon, PC, and flexible filaments) with my unlocked Davinci (luc's repetier firmware is great!) I designed a drop in replacement that only needs some M3 hardware, an MK8 extruder gear, a 624 roller bearing, E3Dv6 hotend, and 5V fan (30x30x10 for the E3D itself, or 40x40x10 for print cooling with a permanent 12V power source for the E3D fan). I made it so you can use the original brass sleeve bearings (I know they're not the greatest - I'm making a version that will use LM8UU's) but this minimizes bought parts. Just print the carriage, extruder and accessories (belt clip, opto trigger, extruder arm, fan shroud, and fan connectors, board mount - sounds like a lot but it all fits on one plate) and should fit great. The brass sleeves fit well and can be tightened if your tolerances are better than mine. You'll need to transplant the board from the original extruder - just wire up the fan, heater, thermistor and extruder the same way from the board. As far as software goes, I'll be adding a version that uses an MK7 gear that should work with the stock extruder calibration, (maybe without any firmware changes!) but for now you'll need luc's repetier firmware with the following changes: " #define EXT0_STEPS_PER_MM 165" I've had issues with this and I just put M92 E165 in the start gcode DO NOT change thermistor type, it is a 104gt-2 i the stock and e3d, but the temp table is custom for their resistor values. "#define MAXTEMP 305 // to go up to 30" "#define MAX_DEFECT_TEMPERATURE 325 //increased as well" And finally you'll need either:
a 5v 30x30x10 fan instead of the e3d 12v fan
or a 5V 40x40x10mm fan for the print cooler Davinci controls fans with 5v so in the original config, the same 5V just controls the e3d fan. If you want a fan to cool the prints, you'll need a 5v 40x40x10 fan so davinci can control it. You'll also need to change near the beginning of the configuration.h: " #define REPURPOSE_FAN_TO_COOL_EXTRUSIONS 0 //Setting this to 1 will repurpose the main Extruder cooling fan to be controlled VIA M106/M107 " Set this to 1 and davinci will control the print cooling fan, but you need to find a permanent power source for the e3d fan (12v for stock or 5v if you got one)/
